description: Event 1Title: Identidades híbridas y (des/re)territorialización en la literatura hispana y sus exilios (1939–1979)Date & Time: Wednesday, May 1st, 10:30 a.m.Location: Academic Building West, Room 5050Language: SpanishIn this lecture, Dr. Enrique Muñoz-Mantas (University of North Dakota) will explore the formation of hybrid identities and the processes of (dis/re)territorialization in Hispanic literature written in exile between 1939 and 1979. Drawing from transatlantic and decolonial frameworks, the talk will examine how writers displaced by the Spanish Civil War and subsequent dictatorships negotiated cultural memory, spatial dislocation, and linguistic identity. Dr. Muñoz-Mantas will highlight the aesthetic and political strategies through which exiled authors reframed notions of homeland, authorship, and subjectivity across fragmented geographies. The presentation will be of special interest to those working on exile studies, Latin American and Iberian literature, and political aesthetics.   Event 2Title: De doctorando a doctor en el mercado laboral en Estados Unidos: estrategias clave y recursosDate & Time: Wednesday, May 1st, 5:00 p.m.Location: Academic Building West, Room 5190Language: SpanishThis professional development workshop, led by Dr. Enrique Muñoz-Mantas, offers an in-depth, practical session for graduate students preparing for the academic job market in the United States. With a focus on the particular challenges faced by international and bilingual candidates, the workshop will address key strategies for assembling competitive job materials, navigating hiring practices in U.S. academia, and translating graduate training into viable professional profiles. Attendees will also learn about essential resources and institutional expectations to support a successful transition from doctoral studies to academic careers. The workshop will include time for Q&A and personalized discussion, making it especially valuable for students in the final stages of their doctoral journey.
name: Identidades híbridas y (des/re)territorialización en la literatura hispana y sus exilios (1939–1979) + De doctorando a doctor en el mercado laboral en Estados Unidos: estrategias clave y recursos
organizationName: Literary Studies in Spanish Organization (Graduate Organization)

description: Join JVCA as we appreciate two recently released Japanese short films, Look Back (2024) and Summer Ghost (2021)! This event will have free pizza and drinks, so be sure to stop by our last meeting of the semester! Read some reviews of the movies below: “There’s a haiku-like purity to it: Look Back is as neat and yet also as overflowing as the four-panel strips in which its leads once diligently honed their craft. And if something so beautiful also feels too brief – well, that may be the idea.” -Robbie Collin, The Telegraph “Summer Ghost is an incredibly profound and emotionally moving film. It left a deep impression on me, especially since I’ve felt almost numb to emotions lately. However, this movie was different—it pushed me forward in ways I didn’t expect. After watching it, I came to a powerful realization: my life matters... It also teaches us to follow our dreams and live with purpose. Even though I don’t fully understand what love feels like, the emotions in this film touched me in a way that feels rare and special. It’s not just a movie; it’s a reminder of the beauty and potential in life.” -Srv Frosti, Google Reviews
name: JVCA Short Films Night

description: Hi everyone,   RU Nu Rho Psi's annual research conference, AXON, is coming up soon! All students who are conducting neuroscience-related research are invited to present their research projects to an audience for the chance to win cash prizes. This year, AXON will be held on May 3rd from 1230pm - 5pm in room 105 of the Psychology Building on Busch Campus. Students at Rutgers have the option to present their research via presentation of a physical printed poster during a poster session, or via a 15 minute slideshow presentation (10 minute talk + 5 minutes for questions). Students would not only be able to present their research at a conference recognized by the National Honor Society of Neuroscience, they would also have the chance to get their presentations judged for the possibility of winning a cash prize (a $100 prize, a $75 prize, and a $50 prize will be awarded). Attending and presenting at AXON is completely free, and food will be provided and catered. There will also be a keynote speaker presenting on the topic of Social Media and the Brain. All interested students must complete the following abstract submission and conference registration forms by this Sunday, 4/27. Abstract Submission Form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSf-vghSBWkJf9olPG1CCrvmg9B9-wkUhs6hKIDjZLt7LG8cFQ/viewform?usp=header Conference Registration Form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdVoZVMbU5KhTDDvuVC0wuiWR55IKkPP6MTNSqY19SH6NarlQ/viewform?usp=header  For more information, including a tentative schedule, please visit the following website: http://axon2025.myportfolio.com/ Hope to see you there!
name: AXON 6.0 Neuroscience Research Conference

description: The annual Rites of Passage Ceremony is a pre-commencement celebration that centers the experiences and culture of Black and Latine-identified students who, through resolute persistence, have completed an undergraduate or graduate degree at Rutgers University–New Brunswick. The event recognizes their accomplishments, hard work, and dedication while acknowledging the substantial efforts of our student’s families and networks of support. Distinguished speakers, student awards, performances, and the incorporation of African and Latine culture and traditions—specifically the culminating Kente Stole presentation—all add to the vibrancy of this celebratory day. Participation in the Rites of Passage Ceremony is open to all Rutgers University—New Brunswick Undergraduate and Graduate students who have earned their degrees between January 2025 and August 2025.  To participate, students must register by Friday, May 2nd, 2025 through the getINVOLVED portal. Only students registered by the deadline will be guaranteed Rites of Passage graduate perks and able to ensure you have tickets for guests.  All graduates are required to wear their academic regalia, which can be purchased from the Barnes and Noble Rutgers University Bookstore on Somerset Street. There is no cost to participate in Rites of Passage for graduates or guests. All graduates who register will receive the following:-1 Free Kente Cloth Stole-7 guest tickets-Access to reception - Digital Invitation Downloads  If you have specific questions about your registration or the ceremony, please email rop@echo.rutgers.edu. Please note that all graduates need to be checked-in between 2:30-3:30pm. The graduation will start promptly at 4:00pm.  Visit the Rites of Passage website for more information!
name: 33rd Annual Rites of Passage Ceremony Registration
organizationNames: Center for Latino Arts and Culture

organizationName: Together Educating All Children in Hospitals

description: Join us for a Resume Review Workshop designed to help you craft a product-focused resume that stands out! Whether you're seeking your first product role, pivoting into product management, or aiming to level up your career, this event is for you. You'll receive personalized feedback from experienced product professionals, learn what recruiters look for, and gain actionable tips to highlight your impact, skills, and leadership potential.
name: Resume Review

description: Anyone interested in the dental field, or wants to explore a unique field come to learn about our club and meet the E-board. We are happy to answer any questions or just come to listen and meet other people interested in the similar things as you!
